Going to jump in to clarify a few things here.

A: We're basically talking Crimson Skies shit here. If Crimson Skies triggers you, then you're just going to have to get used to being triggered.
B: Anthros are not simply swapped in. Anthros come entirely from the geographically isolated island of Avalon, and got wherever else they are by emigration. All anthros are ethnically Avalonian. It's more Atlantis and less Battlefield.
C:Autism is part of making a world internally consistent. I'll admit that some doses of Tom Clancy may have snuck in while I've worked on Lining, but there is a huge gulf between the autism used to develop and maintain a world and what the reader ever actually gets told. All that only exists so you can make sure what your reader does see makes sense and is believable.

The bottom line is we're talking Crimson Skies here, and you really shouldn't be taking it too seriously

Historiccal coexistion is the best since it allows for the taboo and the lack of actual knowledge from them, as you can make them secretive/isolationist and unwilling to share any of their culture with anyone, making them a mystery to anyone and rare, exotic and also fun. You can have the period of timid integration as both societies start to warm up to one another and do stuff like modern day humans in mostly anthro places and vice versa, with the whole cultural shock and exotic curiosity theme being rather enjoyable.

Scientific creation is my second prefered method as it always puts them in a bit of a pedestal and a precarious situation. They are to be trated as equals but probably have the whole creation complex and it can make a interesting dynamic, like a country that spawned from a colony and the like. No explanation is fine enough, especialy for the shorter stuff.

Interdimensional travel is something I just dont really care for, as any race thats so technologicaly advanced is reaching sparkle oc levels of flake and I just aint into space waifurs.

2 main problems I had when writing sex scenes:
>I over-described the actions
I would do shit like say where every single character's hands are, regardless of if it actually adds to the scene or not.
>I mentioned the dick too much
I can't really describe this one properly. Just, if you're writing about a character pulling their dick out, try and say something like
>He took his pants off
instead of
>Anon's pants dropped, revealing his dick
I can't really explain why it's bad, it just sounds worse. That isn't to say you should never mention the genitals by name, I personally just mentioned them too much.

Overall I changed the amount of and type of details I try to include, which left a lot of my earlier written stuff not being rewritable to my new approach.
